<<.from-version "5.5.0">>

The optional parameter <<.place B>> specifies the input date format. If omitted, it defaults to `JS`. The parameter can be one of the following supported input formats:

|!Format |!Description |
|^`JS` |The input string is interpreted as a date in [[ECMAScript date format|https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-date-time-string-format]]. This format is a subset of ISO 8601. It is used for example by the HTML5 date/time input fields. Expanded years are ''not supported''.|
|^`TW` |The input string is interpreted as a native TiddlyWiki date string (17-digit UTC format).|
|^`UNIXTIME` or `NUMBER` |The input string is interpreted as a signed integer unix timestamp in milliseconds.|
|^`AUTO` |Automatically first tries `JS`. If that fails and the input is a signed integer, it is interpreted as a `UNIXTIME`/`NUMBER` timestamp. Finally, it falls back to loose date parsing with ordinal suffix and comma cleanup (for example `1st`, `2nd`, `3rd`, `4th`, and embedded commas).|

The output is always a 17-digit UTC TiddlyWiki date string. To display the result in another form, chain the [[format Operator]] — for example `format:date[TIMESTAMP]` for a unix timestamp, `format:date[YYYY0MM0DD0hh0mm0ss0XXX]` for a local-time 17-digit string, or any other [[DateFormat]] template.

If the input string does not contain a valid date, the output is an empty list.

